revisions.rev:
The [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] will feature 32 teams. One place was allocated to the hosts, {{nft|Brazil}}, but no automatic place is given to the defending champions, {{nft|Spain}}. The remaining 31 places will be determined by a qualification process, in which entrants from among the other 207 teams from the six [[FIFA]] confederations will compete. Most qualification will be determined within these confederations, with a limited number of inter-confederation play-offs occurring at the end of the process. {{nft|Brunei}}, {{nft|Bhutan}}, {{nft|Guam}} and {{nft|Mauritania}} did not enter.<ref>[http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminarydraw/index.html 2014 FIFA World Cup Brazil Preliminary Draw]</ref> The first qualification match was played on 15 June 2011 and the [[Belizean people|Belizean]] striker [[Deon McCauley]] scored the first goal of the tournament. As of 26 November 2011, 136 teams remain in contention for 31 remaining qualification places. The originally published schedule would have consisted of 824 qualifying matches,<ref>{{cite news|title=Das LosglÃ¼ck bleibt dem DFB-Team treu|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/wm/startseite/555870/artikel_das-losglueck-bleibt-dem-dfb-team-treu.html|trans_title=The luck of the draw remains faithful to the German Team|accessdate=8 October 2011|newspaper=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|Kicker]]|language=German|date=30 July 2011}}</ref> but the withdrawal of the {{nft|Bahamas}} and {{nft|Mauritius}} means only 816 will be required.<ref>
[http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/news/newsid=1496896/index.html Bahamas withdraw from 2014 World Cup Qualifiers] FIFA.com. Retrieved 13 October 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/news/newsid=1535094/index.html |title=Mauritius withdraw from FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=FIFA.com |date=31 October 2011 }}</ref>

